{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774396053,"nonce":"CHMGdgsGz5ddhmpw3yAIMyTlC4U=","title":"SISU-conditional velocity modulation absent despite all prerequisites being met","message":"## The Puzzle\n\nPAI-ASF networks trained with perturbations + adaptive control cost (loss_update) exhibit ALL the ingredients for SISU-dependent peak velocity modulation, yet the effect does not appear:\n\n1. **SISU is used by the network** — endpoint accuracy improves ~11% at moderate SISU (0.0070 → 0.0062), confirming the signal reaches the controller\n2. **Perturbation training changes the policy** — peak velocity drops (3.33 → 2.4-2.6 with adaptive control cost), lateral deviation halves\n3. **Speed headroom exists** — the adaptive control cost successfully moves the network off ceiling speed\n4. **The velocity change is real** — it's a policy difference visible in unperturbed straight reaches, not a perturbation artifact\n\nYet the SISU → velocity effect is \u003c1% across all conditions tested (standard, CVaR, APT, with/without loss_update, pert_std 1-20). The network adopts a UNIFORMLY more robust policy rather than a SISU-conditional one.\n\n## Why This Is Strange\n\nThe network learns: \"when trained on perturbations with high control cost, use moderate forces always.\" It does NOT learn: \"when SISU=1, use higher forces; when SISU=0, use lower forces.\" This is despite SISU providing exactly the information needed to discriminate these cases.\n\nThe accuracy modulation (point 1) shows the network CAN condition its behavior on SISU. But it only does so for feedback gains (corrective responses), not for the feedforward trajectory (velocity profile). This is consistent with the LQG separation principle — optimal control under expected-cost objectives separates the trajectory plan (which ignores uncertainty) from the feedback law (which responds to it). But APT and CVaR approximate worst-case, not expected-cost, objectives. Even those don't produce the velocity signature.\n\n## Possible Explanations\n\n- **Loss landscape**: The running cost loss (constant position penalty from go cue) may create a loss landscape where the optimal strategy under ANY perturbation distribution is the same trajectory shape, just with different feedback gains. The velocity-modulation signature requires the TRAJECTORY PLAN to change with SISU, not just the gains.\n\n- **GRU capacity**: The GRU may lack the representational capacity to maintain two distinct trajectory generators (fast/low-robustness vs slow/high-robustness) and switch between them based on SISU. It instead learns one compromise trajectory. See Bug: ce34c2c.\n\n- **Training signal insufficiency**: With alpha=0.005 and updates every 100 iterations, the adaptive control cost converges to nn_output_weight ~3-4e-5 (only 3-4× above initial 1e-5). This may not create enough speed headroom. A much larger control penalty (e.g., nn_output=1e-2 or higher) might be needed to push the network far enough off ceiling that SISU-conditional modulation becomes optimal.\n\n- **PAI-ASF averaging**: PAI-ASF trains over beta ~ U[0,1] jointly. The network learns the average-case optimal policy across all beta values, which may be a single trajectory + variable gains. An explicit curriculum (train separate epochs at beta=0 vs beta=1, then fine-tune on U[0,1]) might force the network to develop distinct strategies.\n\n## Experimental Evidence\n\nSee results/part2_5/README.md for full tables. Key numbers:\n\n| Condition | Peak vel | SISU 0→1 Δvel |\n|---|---|---|\n| baseline (no loss_update, pert_std=1) | 3.329 | -0.1% |\n| ratio=0.3, pert_std=1, loss_update | 2.424 | +0.2% |\n| ratio=0.3, pert_std=10, loss_update | 2.435 | +0.6% |\n| APT (no loss_update) | 3.27-3.31 | -0.3% to +0.1% |\n\nAPT + loss_update experiment in progress (session 31fa1977).\n\n## Cross-references\n\n- Bug: 31043a5 — Adaptation vs robustness distinguishability\n- Bug: ce34c2c — GRU laziness and architecture choice\n- Bug: c05998e — Part 2.5 experiment umbrella","files":null}]}